+{"id":"frankenjax-8plm","title":"Concatenate overflows output axis for zero-element huge dims","description":"[HIGH] Latest Concatenate oracle coverage added normal and empty-array cases, but crates/fj-lax/src/tensor_ops.rs still computes the concatenated axis with unchecked u32 addition at line 849: tensors.iter().map(|t| t.shape.dims[axis]).sum(). Valid zero-element tensors can carry very large dimensions because Shape::element_count multiplies in u64 and any zero dimension yields element_count=0, so TensorValue::new accepts shapes like [u32::MAX, 0] with an empty element vector.\n\nRepro: create a = TensorValue::new(DType::I64, Shape { dims: vec![u32::MAX, 0] }, vec![]) and b = TensorValue::new(DType::I64, Shape { dims: vec![1, 0] }, vec![]), wrap them as Value::Tensor, set params { \"dimension\": \"0\" }, then call eval_primitive(Primitive::Concatenate, &[a, b], &params). Current debug/test builds panic when summing u32::MAX + 1; optimized builds can wrap the output axis to 0 and return the wrong shape.\n\nExpected: use checked addition for the concatenated axis and return a typed EvalError when the output axis exceeds u32::MAX; also use checked multiplication for total output element count before allocating. Add a regression test using the zero-element huge-dim repro so it does not allocate.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-29T07:59:33.400719541Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-29T07:59:33.400719541Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
